# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] On November 7, 1893, a referendum on women's suffrage was held in Colorado that secured women's voting rights.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Subsequently, Colorado became the first American state to enact women's suffrage by popular referendum.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Before Colorado, two western states and territories had already granted women's suffrage, namely Wyoming and Utah.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Influenced by the actions of female activists in those states, Colorado's own suffrage movement began to gain traction in the 1870s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Throughout the earlier half of the decade, many propositions urging legislators to grant suffrage were defeated.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] On January 10, 1876, suffrage advocates held a convention at the Unity Church in Denver, intending to influence the state's constitutional convention.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] The convention established the Territorial Women's Suffrage Society, which turned into the Women's Suffrage Association of Colorado once Colorado was granted statehood.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] The Non-Partisan Equal Suffrage Association was eventually backed by Governor John Routt.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] A minority report was created and sent to the convention.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Women were not granted the right to vote, but they were granted the right to vote in school elections and hold school offices.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] With the backing of John Routt, the women's suffrage movement gained traction.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] In 1877, male legislators decided to hold a referendum to determine the voting status of women.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Although the movement gained the recognition of many popular suffrage advocates, such as Susan B.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Legislative efforts between 1877 and 1893 were sparse.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] In 1881, a bill for municipal suffrage was sent to Legislature and lost.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] However, during that time, many grassroots organizations still were still holding meetings and advocating for women's rights.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] In 1893, the Ninth General Assembly passed a motion to put the question of women's suffrage up for election.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] As a result, the Colorado Non-Partisan Equal Suffrage Association was integral to the 1893 referendum.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] It was a grassroots coalition of women's organizations, churches, political parties, charity groups, unions and farmers alliances.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Having no members or money to their name, the organization toured around the state, rallying for support.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Their campaign pivoted to directly address the women of Colorado: "Women of Colorado, do you know the opportunity that is before you this fall?
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Do you know that there is a possibility you may rise to legal equality with man?" one leaflet asked the state's women.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Warner Mills of Denver and sponsored by Rep.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] After the bill was presented in the Colorado General Assembly, anti-suffragists placed a copy of their journal, the *Remonstrance,* on the desk of ever legislator.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] The suffrage bill left committee and went to the House on January 24, 1893.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] After a first attempt, the bill failed in the house by 39 to 21.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] It was then introduced in the Senate and passed there on April 3 by 20 to 10.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Then the bill was signed by governor Davis Hanson Waite.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] The general election where the referendum would appear would be held in fall of 1893.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] In the end, 55% of the electorate turned out to vote, with 35,798 voting in favor and 29,551 voting against.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] *The Delta Independent* had a headline that read "Women will vote in this state just like a man" after women won the vote.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] In the months after the passing of the 1893 Suffrage Bill, the number of women learning political history skyrocketed.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] One Denver firm reported selling a larger number of books on political economy during the first eight months than they had in the 20 years before.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] The following year, three Colorado women - Clara Cressingham, Carrie Clyde Holly and Frances Klock - became the first women to be elected to any legislature in U.S. history when they were elected to the Colorado House of Representatives.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] However, despite this support, the General Assembly was almost entirely controlled by men.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Women were, however, able to exert their influence a little, through the enaction of Prohibition bills.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Even after legislation passed, the Non-Partisan Equal Suffrage Association remained active for many years, advocating for suffrage in other states across America.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] In 1919 the US congress voted in favor of the 19th amendment and needed 36 states to vote in its favor.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] This amendment was ratified on December 15, 1920, by Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum] Colorado was one of 35 other states that had recognized women's suffrage rights in 1920.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The anti-suffrage movement was a counter movement opposing the social movement of women's suffrage in various countries.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] It could also be considered a counter public that espoused a democratic defense of the status quo for women and men in society.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Countries in the Western World began to explore giving women the equal right to vote around the mid 19th century, beginning with the Wyoming Territory in 1869.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Areas with the most visible women's suffrage movements were Great Britain and in the United States, although women's suffrage movements took place in many Western countries.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffrage activities began to emerge in many countries as women publicly advocated for suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffrage movements were present in Australia through the 1880s and 1890s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The Australian anti-suffragist movement was founded on a platform of patriotism.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Australia stood out as one of the few members of the British Empire where women held the right to vote at the turn of the twentieth century.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Consequently, they were held accountable when the 1916 referendum on compulsory overseas military service was defeated.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Publications advocating anti-suffragism utilized the emotions and politics surrounding forced enlistment for men to argue against women's enfranchisement in other parts of the empire.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In the lead-up to the 1917 referendum, feminine emotionalism was cited as evidence that women had no place in politics.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Newspaper coverage of the referendum placed blame on women's belief that "they would be condemning men to death if they voted 'yes'." Anti-suffragists consistently pointed to the defeat of Australia's referendums as evidence to support their assertion of the universal unreliability of women voters.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Even in the face of loyal efforts by Australian women, such as those within the Australian Women's National League (AWNL), opponents of suffrage persisted in characterizing Australian women's participation in the referendums as a failure to fulfill their responsibilities.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Canadian men and women both became involved in debating the women's suffrage movement in the late 19th century.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Women's suffrage was debated in the Legislative Assembly in New Brunswick starting in 1885, and anti-suffrage "testimonies" began to appear in the newspapers around that time.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Organized campaigns against women's suffrage began in earnest in 1905, around the same time that suffragettes were turning to militant tactics.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In general, most ordinary women had prioritized domestic and family life over paid employment and political activism when it came to the issue of suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Most historical evidence shows that ordinary women did not have much interest in the right to vote before the first World War and also after suffrage had been granted to women.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The Women's National Anti-Suffrage League was established in London on 21 July 1908.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Its aims were to oppose women being granted the vote in British parliamentary elections, although it did support their having votes in local government elections.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] It was founded at a time when there was a resurgence of support (though still by a minority of women) for the women's suffrage movement.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The Women's National Anti-Suffrage League, publisher of the *Anti-Suffrage Review*, submitted a petition to Parliament in 1907 with 87,500 names, but it was rejected by the Petitions Committee of Parliament as "informal".
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The *Anti-Suffrage Review* also used shame as a tool to fight against the suffrage movement.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] An Anti-suffrage correspondence had taken place in the pages of *The Times* through 1906–1907, with further calls for leadership of the anti-suffrage movement being placed in *The Spectator* in February 1908.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Possibly as early as 1907, a letter was circulated to announce the creation of a National Women's Anti-Suffrage Association and inviting recipients to become a member of the Central Organising Committee or a member.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] It was issued under the names of thirty peeresses who would become prominent anti-suffragists, as well as a number of peers and MPs.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] However, the first meeting of the Women's National Anti-Suffrage League only took place the following year on 21 July, at the Westminster Palace Hotel with Lady Jersey in the chair.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Seventeen persons were nominated to the central committee at this meeting, including Mrs Humphry Ward in the chair of the Literary Committee and Gertrude Bell as secretary.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Frederic Harrison, Miss Lonsdale, Violet Markham and Hilaire Belloc MP.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Beatrice Chamberlain served as the editor of the *Anti-Suffrage Review*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The League's aims were to oppose women being granted the parliamentary franchise, though it did support their having votes in local and municipal elections.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] It published the *Anti-Suffrage Review* from December 1908 until 1918.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] It gathered 337,018 signatures on an anti-suffrage petition and founded the first local branch in Hawkenhurst in Kent.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The first London branch was established in South Kensington under the auspices of Mary, Countess of Ilchester.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Soon after, in May 1910, a Scottish branch was organised into the Scottish National Anti-Suffrage League by the Duchess of Montrose.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] By December of that year, there were 26 branches or sub-branches in the country, a total which grew to 82 by April 1909, and 104 in July 1910.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] It was announced that 2000 subscriptions had been received by December, 1908, rising to 9000 in July, 1909.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In 1910, the group amalgamated with the Men's League for Opposing Woman Suffrage to form the National League for Opposing Women's Suffrage with Lord Cromer as president and Lady Jersey as vice-president.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The merger was in effect a takeover, as the president of the former organization, Lord Cromer, became president of the new one.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In 1912 Lord Curzon and Lord Weardale became joint presidents.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The organization continued its activities and the publication of the *Anti-Suffrage Review* until 1918 when both came to an end as women's suffrage was granted.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The opposition to the right for women to vote was a multifaceted phenomenon in which women themselves played a major part.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists were also appalled by the violent tactics of suffragettes, who had attacked Members of Parliament with whips and a hatchet.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Many female maternal reformers, who sought to protect women's defined spheres of motherhood, education, philanthropy, and civil service, felt that women were the better sex for preserving British society through social service to their communities rather than by being involved with politics.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Since Britain was in the process of colonizing other regions around the globe, some viewed the right to vote as a threat to their imperial power as it would make the British look weak to other nations who were male oriented still.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Some suffragist female groups developed militant and violent tactics which tarnished the image of women as peaceful people that the anti-suffragists had been striving to preserve.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists used these acts as reasons to show that women were unable to handle political matters and that both genders had different strengths.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Women writers promoted anti-suffragism through their wide readerships by raising questions of what ideal women were to be like.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Women's suffrage movements had been going on in Ireland since the 1870s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] However, as Suffragettes in Ireland became more militant, more organized anti-suffrage campaigns emerged.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] An Irish branch of the Women's National Anti-Suffrage League was started in 1909 in Dublin.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] This branch of the League also opposed suffrage in Britain as well.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Irish opposition to the women's vote was both religious and cultural.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Both Catholic and Protestant churches in Ireland wanted women's influence to remain domestic in nature.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Women were closely associated with their husbands for legal and political purposes and it was argued that husband's votes were sufficient to allow a woman's political expression.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Irish nationalism also played a role in anti-suffrage movements.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Because of the nationalistic movements going on in Ireland, both men and women nationalists opposed giving women the vote because they were prioritizing Irish Home Rule.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] A nationalist paper, *Bean na hÉireann,* which was published by the Inghinidhe na hÉirann (Daughters of Ireland), took a very anti-suffrage stance.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The American Revolution established universal ideas of equality and natural rights as the hallmark of American policy.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] This juxtaposed women's customary and now legal exclusion with the public sanctions they had been granted to act politically in the role of the Republican wife or mother and the competency displayed by female politicians.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] An expanding franchise for white men, moved political action indoors and women to the periphery.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] While men were involved in the anti-suffrage movement in the United States, most anti-suffrage groups were led and supported by women.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In fact, more women joined Anti-suffrage groups than suffrage associations, until 1916.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] While these groups openly stated that they wanted politics to be left to men, it was more often women addressing political bodies with anti-suffrage arguments.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The first women-led anti-suffrage group in the United States was the Anti-Sixteenth Amendment Society.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The group was started by Madeleine Vinton Dahlgren in 1869.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] During the fight to pass the nineteenth amendment, women increasingly took on a leading role in the anti-suffrage movement.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Helen Kendrick Johnson's *Woman and the Republic* (1897) was a lauded anti-suffrage book that described the reasons for opposing women's right to vote.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffrage dramas were also published between the mid-1800s and up to the 1920s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The first playwright to create anti-suffrage plays was William Bentley Fowle, who wrote the one-act play for amateurs, *Women's Rights*, published in 1856.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Later plays were adapted for the professional stage, such as *The Rights of Man* (1857) by Oliver S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Leland and *Election Day* (1880) by Frank Dumont.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Nellie Locke published an anti-suffrage drama in 1896, called *A Victim of Women's Rights*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Many anti-suffrage dramas were overtly political and incorporated the use of farce to paint suffragists as "self-absorbed" and "mannish in dress and manner." They also criticized the idea of the New Woman in general and advocated for women and men to occupy separate spheres of influence.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The anti-suffrage movement began in the United States after the Massachusetts State legislature introduced a proposal to promote female voting rights.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Two hundred women opposed this initiative as they did not want women to gain full citizenship.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Though nothing became of this proposal, its introduction mobilized the suffrage movement on both sides.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In 1871, a petition to the United States Congress was published by nineteen women in Godey's Lady's Book and Magazine in opposition to votes for women, the first instance of the mobilization from anti-suffrage women.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Women turned out at the New York State Constitutional Convention in 1894 to protest women's suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In 1895, the Massachusetts Association Opposed to the Further Extension of Suffrage to Women (MAOFESW) was created and is noted to be the first effort of the anti-suffragists to institutionalize their cause.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In Des Moines, Iowa, 35 women formed the Iowa Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage in 1898.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] California, Illinois, New York, Oregon, South Dakota and Washington all formed groups by 1900.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Ohio formed an anti suffrage group, the Ohio Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage in 1902.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The New York State Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage was founded in 1897, and by 1908 it had over 90 members.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] It was active in producing pamphlets and publications explaining their views of women's suffrage, until the Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution was passed in 1920.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The suffragists in New York often extended invitations to open discussion with the anti-suffragists.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The New York association had its own magazine, *The Anti-Suffragist*, published by Mrs.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] William Winslow Crannell from July 1908 to April 1912.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The National Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage (NAOWS) was the first national organization of women who challenged the fight for women's suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Several state associations assembled for an anti-suffrage convention in New York City and formed the NAOWS.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The association gained significant momentum between 1912 and 1916 and was operational in twenty-five states.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The NAOWS was said to have as many as 350,000 members.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] At the start, the organization was run by Josephine Dodge and Minnie Bronson.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Alice Hay Wadsworth, wife of James Wolcott Wadsworth Jr., assumed leadership of the association when it moved its headquarters from New York to Washington, D.C. in 1917.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] NAOWS produced *The Woman's Protest*, a newsletter that helped defeat close to forty woman suffrage referendums.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Wheeler, a lawyer from New York, created the Man-Suffrage Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage in 1913.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] This organization was made up of powerful and affluent men and started out with around 600 members opposed to women's suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The cause of anti-suffragism was furthered by the friction between the women's and black suffrage movements prior to the ratification of the Fifteenth Amendment.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The connection between the two movements arose during the 1830s when abolitionist activists' rhetoric linked the subordination of enslaved people to the marginalization of women.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Figures like William Lloyd Garrison, leader of the American Anti-Slavery Society, advocated for the collaboration of women and blacks in their respective causes.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] However, other abolitionists argued that simultaneous promotion of women's rights would detract from the cause of black suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] By 1869, a split between race and gender had formed.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Pioneers of the women's suffrage movement, such as Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anthony, adopted overtly racist rhetoric that served to distance the causes of women's and black suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] This division has been attributed to a number of factors, including personal biases of women suffragists.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] However, some scholars argue for a reexamination of the assumption that women's suffrage was "ahead of its time" during the Reconstruction era.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Relations between the two movements soured when the 1867 Kansas suffrage referendum proved unsuccessful for both causes.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Women suffragists found themselves unable to endorse the conditions of the Fifteenth Amendment, which granted voting rights to black men but omitted provisions for women's suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Dudden suggests that the content of Stanton and Anthony's speeches in the year prior to the Fifteenth Amendment's ratification indicates their belief that they were capitalizing on a historic moment of political opportunity that would not recur in their lifetime.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Wendell Phillips, a trustee of the Hovey Fund, denied access to the capital necessary to launch their campaign.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Consequently, the conflict over money misdirected the suffragists' attentions from Phillips to the Black Suffragism movement he funded instead.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Ultimately, the instability between the two parties would prolong the cause of anti-suffragists for another fifty years until the Nineteenth Amendment was ratified in 1920.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists helped contribute to war relief work during World War I.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] NAOWS contributed to the Belgian war relief effort.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Many anti-suffrage groups highlighted their charitable efforts, painting themselves as "self-sacrificing." They wanted the country to see that women could make a difference without the vote, however, it was partly the efforts of women aiding the war that helped women gain the vote in the end.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] There were several concerns that drove the anti-suffrage argument.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists felt that giving women the right to vote would threaten the family institution.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Illinois anti-suffragist, Caroline Corbin felt that women's highest duties were motherhood and its responsibilities.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Some saw women's suffrage as in opposition to God's will.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Antis such as Catharine Beecher and Sara Josepha Hale both shared a religiously based criticism of suffrage and believed women should be only involved with *Kinder, Küche, Kirche* (children, kitchen and church).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Some anti-suffragists did not want the vote because they felt it violated traditional gender norms.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] There were also those who thought that women could not handle the responsibility of voting because they lacked knowledge of that beyond the domestic sphere and they feared the government would be weakened by introducing this ill-informed electorate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists did not see voting as a "right," but as a "duty" and that women already had their own unique responsibilities and duties in the domestic sphere.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists, such as Josephine Dodge, argued that giving women the right to vote would overburden them and undermine their privileged status.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] They saw participation in the private sphere as essential to a woman's role and thought that giving them public duties would prevent them from fulfilling their primary responsibilities in the home.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists claimed that they represented the "silent majority" of America who did not want to enter the public sphere by gaining the right to vote.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Being against women's suffrage didn't mean, however, that all Antis were against civic pursuits.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Gilder, a journalist, wrote "Give women everything she wants, but not the ballot.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The thought was that women were able to influence the government because they were seen as politically neutral and non-partisan and giving them the right to vote would strip them of this unique position.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In addition, because voting is "only a small part of government," they believed there was no need to vote in order to participate in politics.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] This particular line of reasoning, that women should stay out of politics, kept the General Federation of Women's Clubs (GFWC) from officially endorsing suffrage until 1914.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragism was not limited to conservative elements.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The anarchist Emma Goldman opposed suffragism on the grounds that women were more inclined toward legal enforcement of morality (as in the Women's Christian Temperance Union), that it was a diversion from more important struggles, and that suffrage would ultimately not make a difference.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] She also said that activists ought to advocate revolution rather than seek greater privileges within an inherently unjust system.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffragists saw women's efforts to gain the vote to be all surface dressing with a lack of serious intent to change the world for the better.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Other Antis believed that social reform was better accomplished through trade unions and non-partisan groups.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Progressives criticized suffrage in the Utah Territory as a cynical Mormon ploy, resulting in the passage of the Edmunds-Tucker Act.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Another argument employed by anti-suffragists related to the issue of the uninformed voter.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] This argument was grounded not so much in opposition to women's right to vote, but rather in the concern that their participation would exacerbate an already overtaxed ballot system.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Educational requirements were proposed to counter these concerns but became contentious with the ratification of the Fifteenth Amendment.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Educated women voiced their resentment that less educated and frequently illiterate men should have the right to vote before themselves.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The anti-suffrage movement began to change in its position against suffrage in 1917, expanding their scope to include anti-radical rhetoric.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The anti-suffrage movement focused less on the issue of suffrage and began to spread fear of radical ideas and to use "conspiratorial paranoia." Suffragists were accused of subversion of the government and treason.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In addition to associating suffrage with radicalism, the antis also felt that they were oppressed and had lost much perceived political power by 1917.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffrage movements in the American South included an appeal to conservatism and white supremacy.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In Virginia, the NAOWS chapter even linked race riots to women's suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Once the nineteenth amendment was passed, some women who opposed suffrage exercised this right.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] They took the energy they were investing in the anti-suffrage movement and turned it towards supporting the platform of the Republican party.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Former members of anti-suffrage groups in New York became involved in the Women's National Republican Club.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In this way, they left the private sphere and entered the public sphere, one of the things that they were resisting in their anti-suffrage efforts.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Former anti-suffragist, Ida Tarbell, pointed out that it would take some time for women to get comfortable with voting.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Some women didn't vote or get involved in politics.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Others, like Annie Nathan Meyer advocated for all anti-suffrage women to not vote in order to allow the country to suffer from what she saw as a terrible decision to allow women to vote.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In the 2020s, many American far-right figures began to call for the repeal of the Nineteenth Amendment, often connected with the Christian nationalist movement.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] This viewpoint came to more attention in August 2025, when U.S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth reposted a video on Twitter featuring Doug Wilson, pastor of Christ Church in Moscow, Idaho, in which video participants discussed repealing the Nineteenth Amendment.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In response, Hegseth's press secretary clarified that he supports women's suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Other notable political figures connected with this view include Paul Ingrassia, who appeared to endorse this viewpoint in a 2023 podcast interview, Paul Ray Ramsey, Dale Partridge, John Gibbs, and Andrew Tate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-abortion advocate Abby Johnson has advocated replacing the current voting system with one of household voting.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In 2022, American political commentator and a far-right white nationalist, activist, Nick Fuentes told the British journalist Louis Theroux that he believes it would be better if women did not have the right to vote.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] In November 2025, Fuentes said that if he was elected president, he would “just take away the right to vote for tons of people.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] There was contemporary criticism of the anti-suffrage movement in the United States.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] One criticism was that anti-suffragists did not present a consistent argument against suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Other arguments were seen as inconsistent, such as Antis claiming that voting meant women must hold office, when members of anti-suffrage groups were already holding offices such as being on the school board.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Other critics, such as Alice Stone Blackwell, pointed out that the anti-suffrage groups exaggerated certain claims, such as membership numbers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Critics also argued that there were no new arguments presented over time.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] Anti-suffrage groups were also criticized for being "inconsistent" in that they wanted women out of the public sphere, yet they gathered together into public lobbying groups against suffrage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The archives of the Women's National Anti-Suffrage League are held at The Women's Library at the Library of the London School of Economics, ref 2WNA.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The Library and Archives division of the Georgia Historical Society have a collection of broadsides from the National Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage from 1917 to 1919.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] The documents appear to be printed by state affiliates of the national group.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/anti-suffragism] One of the documents was issued by The Men's Anti-Ratification League of Montgomery, Alabama.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] Colorado became the first state in which women obtained the right to vote through popular election in 1893.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] The following year, on November 6, 1894, three women were elected to serve in the Colorado House of Representatives.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] Besides Holly, they included Clara Cressingham and Frances S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] All three were Republicans and were sworn into office in 1895.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] Each served one term, from 1895 to 1896.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] Carrie Holly introduced a total of fourteen bills.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] One became law: a bill that aimed to increase the Age of Consent for girls to 21.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] The outcome was a compromise: the Age of Consent was increased to 18.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] Carrie Holly published a detailed account of the legislative process.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] She did not run for re-election after her first term, although she maintained an active interest in politics and public affairs and was admitted to the bar in 1896.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/carrie-clyde-holly] She was married to the associate justice of the Colorado Territorial Supreme Court Charles Frederick Holly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] Cressingham was born in Brooklyn, New York on October 6, 1863, the daughter of Seth W.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] She was raised in Brooklyn, where she also attended public schooling.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] Cressingham in 1883 and the family moved to Denver in 1890, where her husband worked as a typesetter.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] After she and her husband had moved from New York, she was employed as a writer, and she was the mother of two children when elected to the Colorado General Assembly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] Besides Cressingham, they included Carrie C.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] At 32 years old, Clara Cressingham was the youngest of these three legislators.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] As Secretary of the House Republican Caucus, Cressingham was the first woman to fill a leadership position in an American legislature.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] Cressingham is credited with being the first woman to introduce a law in the United States.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] It set a government–provided bounty of $3 per ton on sugar beets raised in the state and sold to a factory within its borders, thus boosting the budding Colorado sugar beet industry.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] Other bills she introduced during her two years in the House addressed the creation of a state board of arbitration and a system of free schools.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] Along with the other two women in the legislature, she successfully supported a bill to create homes for "delinquent" girls.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/clara-cressingham] Cressingham died in 1906 of "rheumatism of the heart" at the age of 42.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] It is a bicameral legislature consisting of the Senate and House of Representatives that was created by the 1876 state constitution.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Its statutes are codified in the *Colorado Revised Statutes* (C.R.S.).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The session laws are published in the *Session Laws of Colorado*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Colorado's legislature is similar to those of other states, except that, unlike many states, Colorado does not give its lieutenant governor any legislative authority (e.g. tie-breaking vote).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The first meeting of the Colorado General Assembly took place from November 1, 1876, through March 20, 1877.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Succeeding sessions met every two years until 1950, when it began to meet annually.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The lieutenant governor served as Senate President until 1974 when Article V, Section 10 of the state constitution was amended, granting the Colorado Senate the right to elect one of its own members as President.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The Colorado Constitution establishes a system of government based on the separation of powers doctrine with power divided among the executive, legislative and judicial branches of government.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Article V vests the legislative power of the state in the General Assembly, while reserving to the people the power to propose, approve, and reject both laws and amendments to the state Constitution by initiatives or referendums.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The General Assembly is bicameral, composed of the Colorado House of Representatives and the Colorado Senate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The House has 65 members and the Senate 35.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Members of the House are elected to two-year terms, and members of the Senate are elected to four-year terms.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] General legislative elections are held on the first Tuesday after the first Monday in November in each even-numbered year.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The entire House is elected in each general election.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Senators are elected in two classes such that, as nearly as possible, one-half of the senators are elected in each general election.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] House members are limited to four consecutive terms in office, and state senators are limited to two consecutive terms.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] However, term-limited former members of both houses can run again after a four-year break.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] It is also possible for individuals who have been registered to vote and affiliated with the political party in question for at least a year to gain access to a partisan primary ballot by petition.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Minor party candidates can gain access to the general election ballot through a minor party caucus process.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Unaffiliated candidates can gain access to the general election ballot by petition.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Vacancies in legislative offices are generally filled by political party vacancy committees, rather than special elections.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Vacancy appointees who fill the first half of a state senator's term must stand for election at the next even year November election for the remainder of the state senate term for the seat to which the state senator was appointed.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The state auditor is appointed by the General Assembly, as are many members of independent boards and commissions.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Currently, the Colorado General Assembly is controlled by the Democratic Party.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Democrats also hold the governor's office.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The Colorado General Assembly was the first state legislature to welcome women as elected members, with Clara Cressingham, Carrie C.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Klock all being elected to the State House of Representatives in 1894 and Helen Robinson being elected to the State Senate in 1912 (the second state upper house in the country to welcome women as members).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] With the notable exceptions listed below, the Colorado General Assembly operates in a manner quite similar to the United States Congress.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Regular sessions are held annually and begin no later than the second Wednesday in January.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Regular sessions last no more than 120 days.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Special sessions may be called at any time by the governor or upon written request of two-thirds of the members of each house, but are infrequent.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Some committees of the General Assembly work between sessions and have limited power to take action without General Assembly approval between legislative sessions.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Joint procedural rules of the two chambers require most legislation to be introduced very early in the legislative session each year, and to meet strict deadlines for completion of each step of the legislative process.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Joint procedural rules also limit each legislator to introducing five bills per year, subject to certain exceptions for non-binding resolutions, uniform acts, interim committee bills and appropriations bills.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Most members of the General Assembly decide which bills they will introduce during the legislative session (or most of them) prior to its commencement, limiting the ability of members to introduce new bills at constituent request once the legislative session has begun.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Most bills adopted by the General Assembly include a "safety clause" (i.e. a legislative declaration that the bill concerns an urgent matter) and take effect on July 1 following the legislative session unless otherwise provided.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Some bills are enacted without a "safety clause" which makes it possible to petition to subject those bills to a referendum before they take effect, and have an effective date in August following the legislative session unless otherwise provided.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Colorado's legislature does not have an analog to the filibuster in the United States Senate requiring a supermajority for approval of any matter.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The lieutenant governor does not have the power to preside or break tie votes in either house of the General Assembly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] All new executive branch rules are reviewed annually by the legislature and the legislature routinely invalidates some of them each year.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The General Assembly does have subpoena power, However this power is rarely used.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The General Assembly does not have a role in the appointment or retention of state judges, although it must authorize the creation of each judgeship.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Many state agencies and programs are subject to "sunset review" and are automatically abolished if the General Assembly does not reauthorize them.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Before a bill is introduced in the General Assembly, the text typically passes through several stages.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Policy proposals often originate with advocacy organizations, subject-matter experts, or attorneys who identify a need for statutory change.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] A legislator who agrees to sponsor the proposal then submits it to the Office of Legislative Legal Services (OLLS), the non-partisan in-house legal counsel for the General Assembly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] At this point, OLLS will draft or revise the proposed bill text, often in collaboration with the initial advocates or subject-matter experts, to conform to the Colorado Revised Statutes and applicable constitutional requirements.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Co-sponsors may join the bill after the text has been formalized.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The governor submits a proposed budget to the Joint Budget Committee each year in advance of the year's legislative session.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Colorado's fiscal year is from July 1 to June 30.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] All bills introduced in the General Assembly are evaluated by the non-partisan state legislative services body for their fiscal impact and must be provided for in appropriations legislation if there is a fiscal impact.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] A state budget, called the "Long Bill" is prepared each year by the Joint Budget Committee of the General Assembly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Unlike many legislative initiatives, the Long Bill is neither an acronym nor named after an individual with significant influence.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The Long Bill is simply a lengthy bill that contains many appropriations.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The House and the Senate alternate the job of introducing the long bill and making a first committee review of it.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Colorado's state legislature is required to obtain voter approval in order to incur significant debt, to raise taxes, or to increase state constitutional spending limitations.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] It is also required to comply with a state constitutional spending mandate for K-12 education.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The Governor has line item veto power over appropriations.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The Colorado General Assembly is staffed by approximately 230-year-round staff and 115 session-only staff.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Staffing levels and expenditures have decreased since 2003.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Similarly to Congressional staffers, legislative staff in Colorado fall into five broad categories: member staff, administrative staff, committee staff, communications and leadership staff, and legal service staff.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] With the exception of those working in communications and leadership, employees of the General Assembly are non-partisan staffers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] There are 65 House Members and 35 Senate Members making up the 100 seats in Colorado General Assembly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Based on the 2010 census, each House member represents about 77,372 constituents and each Senator 143,691.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The 2018 Colorado elections resulted in Democrats extending their control in the House (41 Democrats; 24 Republicans) and capturing the Senate majority.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] All 65 Colorado House seats were up for election in 2022.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The chamber's Democratic majority increased to 46-19, keeping a supermajority.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] Also, the Democrats kept their majority in the 2022 elections for the Colorado State Senate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The current Senate makeup is 23 Democrats and 12 Republicans.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-general-assembly] The 74th session will mark the first time in state history that women will hold the majority of seats in the General Assembly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] The **Colorado House of Representatives** is the lower house of the Colorado General Assembly, the state legislature of the U.S. state of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] The House is composed of 65 members from an equal number of constituent districts, with each district having roughly 80,000 people.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] Representatives are elected to two-year terms, and are limited to four consecutive terms in office, but can run again after a four-year respite.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] The Colorado House of Representatives convenes at the State Capitol in Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] Woog previously served in the state house from 2021–2023.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] The first women who served in the Colorado House of Representatives were Clara Cressingham, Carrie Holly and Frances Klock.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] All three were elected to serve in 1895-1896.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] Carrie Holly introduced and passed a Bill that raised the age of consent for girls from 16 to 18 and another that gave mothers the same rights to their children as fathers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] A total of 10 women served in the period up to 1904, the last of them being Alice Ruble.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] In 1906, party leaders declared that "no woman will ever again be elected to the [Colorado] legislature".
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-house-of-representatives] Their prediction proved wrong, as demonstrated by the list of subsequent women members of the House - the first of whom was Alma Lafferty, who first served in 1908.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The region has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly much longer.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains was a major migration route for early peoples who spread throughout the Americas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1848, much of the Nuevo México region was annexed to the United States with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Pike's Peak Gold Rush of 1858–1862 created an influx of settlers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On February 28, 1861, U.S. president James Buchanan signed an act creating the Territory of Colorado, and on August 1, 1876, president Ulysses S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Grant signed Proclamation 230, admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Denver is the capital, the most populous city, and the center of the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado Springs is the second-most populous city of the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Residents of the state are known as Coloradans, although the antiquated "Coloradoan" is occasionally used.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado generally ranks as one of the top U.S. states for education attainment, employment, and healthcare quality.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Major parts of its economy include government and defense, mining, agriculture, tourism, and manufacturing.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] With increasing temperatures and decreasing water availability, Colorado's agriculture, forestry, and tourism economies are expected to be heavily affected by climate change.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The region that is today the State of Colorado has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly more than 37,000 years.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Lindenmeier site contains artifacts dating from approximately 8720 BCE.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Ancient Pueblo peoples lived in the valleys and mesas of the Colorado Plateau in far southwestern Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Ute Nation inhabited the mountain valleys of the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Western Rocky Mountains, even as far east as the Front Range of the present day.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Apache and the Comanche also inhabited the Eastern and Southeastern parts of the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In the 17th century, the Arapaho and Cheyenne moved west from the Great Lakes region to hunt across the High Plains of Colorado and Wyoming.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The U.S. acquired the territorial claim to the eastern Rocky Mountains with the Louisiana Purchase from France in 1803.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Army reconnaissance expedition into the disputed region.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colonel Pike and his troops were arrested by Spanish cavalrymen in the San Luis Valley the following February, taken to Chihuahua, and expelled from Mexico the following July.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Under the 1819 Adams-Onís Treaty, the U.S. acquired Florida from Spain while relinquishing claims to lands west of the 100th meridian and south of both the Arkansas River and the 42nd parallel.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The treaty took effect on February 22, 1821.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Having settled its border with Spain, the U.S. admitted the southeastern portion of the Territory of Missouri to the Union as the state of Missouri on August 10, 1821.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The remainder of Missouri Territory, including what would become northeastern Colorado, became an unorganized territory and remained so for 33 years over the question of slavery.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] After 11 years of war, Spain finally recognized the independence of Mexico with the Treaty of Córdoba signed on August 24, 1821.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Mexico eventually ratified the Adams–Onís Treaty in 1831.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Texian Revolt of 1835–36 fomented a dispute between the U.S. and Mexico which eventually erupted into the Mexican–American War in 1846.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Mexico surrendered its northern territory to the U.S. with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo after the war in 1848; this included much of the western and southern areas of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Santa Fe Trail connected the Missouri River to Santa Fe, New Mexico, where it linked with the Camino Real de Tierra Adentro extending southward into Mexico.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Others traveling overland avoided the rugged Southern Rocky Mountains, and instead followed the North Platte River and Sweetwater River to South Pass (Wyoming), the lowest crossing of the Continental Divide between the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Central Rocky Mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1849, the Mormons of the Salt Lake Valley organized the extralegal State of Deseret, claiming the entire Great Basin and all lands drained by the rivers Green, Grand, and Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The federal government of the U.S. flatly refused to recognize the new Mormon government because it was theocratic and sanctioned plural marriage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Instead, the Compromise of 1850 divided the Mexican Cession and the northwestern claims of Texas into a new state and two new territories, the state of California, the Territory of New Mexico, and the Territory of Utah.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Provisional Government of the Territory of Jefferson was an extralegal and unrecognized United States territory that existed in the Pike's Peak mining region from October 24, 1859, until it yielded to the new Territory of Colorado on June 6, 1861.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Jefferson Territory included all of the present State of Colorado and portions of the present states of Kansas, Nebraska, Utah, and Wyoming.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The people were desirous of a closer government than those five territories provided.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The government of the Jefferson Territory, while democratically elected, was never legally recognized by the United States government, although it managed the territory with relatively free rein for 19 months.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Many of the laws enacted by the General Assembly of the Territory of Jefferson were reenacted and given official sanction by the new Colorado General Assembly in 1861.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Territory of Colorado was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from February 28, 1861, until August 1, 1876, when it was admitted to the Union as the 38th State of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The territory was created during the onset of the American Civil War in the wake of the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, which brought the first large concentration of settlers from the east to the region.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The war stifled growth, but following the war mining grew more industrialized and fueled the economy.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The construction of railroads further improved the economy.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The boundaries of the newly designated Colorado Territory were very similar to those of the modern State of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1861 following the beginning of the American Civil War, there were several small disputes and skirmishes between confederate supporters and union supporters.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In August, Governor Gilpin organized the 1st Colorado Infantry.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Slough led the group to New Mexico Territory in February–March 1862.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] There they fought in the battles of Apache Canyon, Glorieta Pass and Peralta.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Slough resigned in April 1862 and was replaced by Major John M.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] With resources tied up in the war there was little left over for mines, farms, and infrastructure, and Denver stagnated.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On March 26, 1862 John Evans was appointed by Abraham Lincoln as the second governor of the territory.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] He prompted investment in Denver rail projects, and founded the University of Denver in 1864.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Anti-native sentiment grew during the Civil War years.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Exterminationist ideology, led in Colorado by Evans and Chivington, advocated for the total eradication of all native people in the territory.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado War worsened relations with natives until 1864 when Chivington ordered the Sand Creek Massacre and Evans was forced to resign the following spring.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1867, the Union Pacific Railroad laid its tracks west to Weir, now Julesburg, in the northeast corner of the Territory.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Union Pacific linked up with the Central Pacific Railroad at Promontory Summit, Utah, on May 10, 1869, to form the First transcontinental railroad.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Denver Pacific Railway reached Denver in June of the following year, and the Kansas Pacific arrived two months later to forge the second line across the continent.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The United States Congress passed an enabling act on March 3, 1875, specifying the requirements for the Territory of Colorado to become a state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On August 1, 1876 (four weeks after the Centennial of the United States), U.S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Grant signed a proclamation admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state and earning it the moniker "Centennial State".
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The discovery of a major silver lode near Leadville in 1878 triggered the Colorado Silver Boom.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Sherman Silver Purchase Act of 1890 invigorated silver mining, and Colorado's last, but greatest, gold strike at Cripple Creek a few months later lured a new generation of gold seekers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado women were granted the right to vote on November 7, 1893, making Colorado the second state to grant universal suffrage and the first one by a popular vote (of Colorado men).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The repeal of the Sherman Silver Purchase Act in 1893 led to a staggering collapse of the mining and agricultural economy of Colorado, but the state slowly and steadily recovered.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Between the 1880s and 1930s, Denver's floriculture industry developed into a major industry in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] This period became known locally as the Carnation Gold Rush.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Both the 1913–1914 Coalfield War and the Denver streetcar strike of 1920 resulted in federal troops intervening to end the violence.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1927, the 1927-28 Colorado coal strike occurred and was ultimately successful in winning a dollar a day increase in wages.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] During it however the Columbine Mine massacre resulted in six dead strikers following a confrontation with Colorado Rangers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In a separate incident in Trinidad the mayor was accused of deputizing members of the KKK against the striking workers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] More than 5,000 Colorado miners—many immigrants—are estimated to have died in accidents since records were first formally collected following an 1884 accident in Crested Butte that killed 59.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1924, the Ku Klux Klan Colorado Realm achieved dominance in Colorado politics.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] With peak membership levels, the Second Klan levied significant control over both the local and state Democrat and Republican parties, particularly in the governor's office and city governments of Denver, Cañon City, and Durango.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] A particularly strong element of the Klan controlled the Denver Police.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Cross burnings became semi-regular occurrences in cities such as Florence and Pueblo.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Klan targeted African-Americans, Catholics, Eastern European immigrants, and other non-White Protestant groups.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Efforts by non-Klan lawmen and lawyers including Philip Van Cise led to a rapid decline in the organization's power, with membership waning significantly by the end of the 1920s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado became the first western state to host a major political convention when the Democratic Party met in Denver in 1908.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] By the U.S. census in 1930, the population of Colorado first exceeded one million residents.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado suffered greatly through the Great Depression and the Dust Bowl of the 1930s, but a major wave of immigration following World War II boosted Colorado's fortune.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Tourism became a mainstay of the state economy, and high technology became an important economic engine.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The United States Census Bureau estimated that the population of Colorado exceeded five million in 2009.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On September 11, 1957, a plutonium fire occurred at the Rocky Flats Plant, which resulted in the significant plutonium contamination of surrounding populated areas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] From the 1940s and 1970s, many protest movements gained momentum in Colorado, predominantly in Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] This included the Chicano Movement, a civil rights, and social movement of Mexican Americans emphasizing a Chicano identity that is widely considered to have begun in Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The National Chicano Youth Liberation Conference was held in Colorado in March 1969.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1967, Colorado was the first state to loosen restrictions on abortion when governor John Love signed a law allowing abortions in cases of rape, incest, or threats to the woman's mental or physical health.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Many states followed Colorado's lead in loosening abortion laws in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Since the late 1990s, Colorado has been the site of multiple major mass shootings, including the Columbine High School massacre in 1999, where high school senior students Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 13 students and one teacher, before committing suicide.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The incident made international news, and has since spawned many copycat incidents, known as the Columbine effect.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On July 20, 2012, a gunman killed 12 people in a movie theater in Aurora.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The state responded with tighter restrictions on firearms, including introducing a limit on magazine capacity.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On March 22, 2021, a gunman killed 10 people, including a police officer, in a King Soopers supermarket in Boulder.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In an instance of anti-LGBT violence, a gunman killed 5 people at a nightclub in Colorado Springs during the night of November 19–20, 2022.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Navy have been named the USS *Colorado*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The first USS *Colorado* was named for the Colorado River and served in the Civil War and later the Asiatic Squadron, where it was attacked during the 1871 Korean Expedition.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The later three ships were named in honor of the state, including an armored cruiser and the battleship USS *Colorado*, the latter of which was the lead ship of her class and served in World War II in the Pacific beginning in 1941.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] At the time of the attack on Pearl Harbor, the battleship USS *Colorado* was located at the naval base in San Diego, California, and thus went unscathed.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The most recent vessel to bear the name USS *Colorado* is Virginia-class submarine USS *Colorado* (SSN-788), which was commissioned in 2018.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado is notable for its diverse geography, which includes alpine mountains, high plains, deserts with huge sand dunes, and deep canyons.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1861, the United States Congress defined the boundaries of the new Territory of Colorado exclusively by lines of latitude and longitude, stretching from 37°N to 41°N latitude, and from 102°02′48″W to 109°02′48″W longitude (25°W to 32°W from the Washington Meridian).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] After 165 years of government surveys, the borders of Colorado were officially defined by 697 boundary markers and 697 straight boundary lines.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado, Wyoming, and Utah are the only states that have their borders defined solely by straight boundary lines with no natural features.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The southwest corner of Colorado is the Four Corners Monument at 36°59′56″N, 109°2′43″W.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument, located at the place where Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah meet, is the only place in the United States where four states meet.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Approximately half of Colorado is flat and rolling land.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] East of the Rocky Mountains is the Colorado Eastern Plains of the High Plains, the section of the Great Plains within Colorado at elevations ranging from roughly 3,350 to 7,500 feet (1,020 to 2,290 m).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado plains are mostly prairies but also include deciduous forests, buttes, and canyons.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Precipitation averages 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado is presently mainly farmland and rangeland, along with small farming villages and towns.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Corn, wheat, hay, soybeans, and oats are all typical crops.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Most villages and towns in this region boast both a water tower and a grain elevator.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Irrigation water is available from both surface and subterranean sources.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Surface water sources include the South Platte, the Arkansas River, and a few other streams.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Subterranean water is generally accessed through artesian wells.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Heavy usage of these wells for irrigation purposes caused underground water reserves to decline in the region.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado also hosts a considerable amount and range of livestock, such as cattle ranches and hog farms.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] About 84% of Colorado's population resides along the eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains in the Front Range Urban Corridor between Cheyenne, Wyoming, and Pueblo, Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] This region is partially protected from prevailing storms that blow in from the Pacific Ocean region by the high Rockies in the middle of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The "Front Range" includes Denver, Boulder, Fort Collins, Loveland, Castle Rock, Colorado Springs, Pueblo, Greeley, and other townships and municipalities in between.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On the other side of the Rockies, the significant population centers in western Colorado (which is known as "The Western Slope") are the cities of Grand Junction, Durango, and Montrose.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] To the west of the Great Plains of Colorado rises the eastern slope of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Notable peaks of the Rocky Mountains include Longs Peak, Mount Blue Sky, Pikes Peak, and the Spanish Peaks near Walsenburg, in southern Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] This area drains to the east and the southeast, ultimately either via the Mississippi River or the Rio Grande into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Rocky Mountains within Colorado contain 53 true peaks and 58 named peaks that are 14,000 feet (4,267 m) or higher in elevation above sea level, known as fourteeners.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] These mountains are largely covered with trees such as conifers and aspens up to the tree line, at an elevation of about 12,000 feet (3,658 m) in southern Colorado to about 10,500 feet (3,200 m) in northern Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Above this tree line, only alpine vegetation grows.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Much of the alpine snow melts by mid-August except for a few snow-capped peaks and a few small glaciers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado Mineral Belt, stretching from the San Juan Mountains in the southwest to Boulder and Central City on the front range, contains most of the historic gold- and silver-mining districts of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The 30 highest major summits of the Rocky Mountains of North America are all within the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The summit of Mount Elbert at 14,437.6 feet (4,400.58 m) elevation in Lake County is the highest point in Colorado and the Rocky Mountains of North America.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado is the only U.S. state that lies entirely above 1,000 meters elevation.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The point where the Arikaree River flows out of Yuma County, Colorado, and into Cheyenne County, Kansas, is the lowest in Colorado at 3,317 feet (1,011 m) elevation.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] This point, which is the highest low elevation point of any state, is higher than the high elevation points of 18 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Continental Divide of the Americas extends along the most of the crest of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The area of Colorado to the west of the Continental Divide is called the Western Slope of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] West of the Continental Divide, water flows to the southwest via the Colorado River and the Green River towards the Gulf of California.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Within the interior of the Rocky Mountains are several large parks which are high broad basins.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In the north, on the east side of the Continental Divide is the North Park of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The North Park is drained by the North Platte River, which flows north into Wyoming and Nebraska.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Just to the south of North Park, but on the western side of the Continental Divide, is the Middle Park of Colorado, which is drained by the Colorado River.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The South Park of Colorado is the region of the headwaters of the South Platte River.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In south-central Colorado is the large San Luis Valley, where the headwaters of the Rio Grande are located.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The northern part of the valley is the San Luis Closed Basin, an endorheic basin that helped created the Great Sand Dunes.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The valley sits between the Sangre de Cristo Mountains and San Juan Mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Rio Grande drains due south into New Mexico, Texas, and Mexico.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Across the Sangre de Cristo Range to the east of the San Luis Valley lies the Wet Mountain Valley.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] These basins, particularly the San Luis Valley, lie along the Rio Grande rift, a major geological formation of the Rocky Mountains, and its branches.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado includes the western face of the Rocky Mountains and all of the area to the western border.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] This area includes several terrains and climates from alpine mountains to arid deserts.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes many ski resort towns in the Rocky Mountains and towns west to Utah.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] It is less populous than the Front Range but includes a large number of national parks and monuments.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The northwestern corner of Colorado is a sparsely populated region, and it contains part of the noted Dinosaur National Monument, which not only is a paleontological area, but is also a scenic area of rocky hills, canyons, arid desert, and streambeds.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Here, the Green River briefly crosses over into Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado is drained by the Colorado River and its tributaries (primarily the Gunnison River, Green River, and the San Juan River).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado River flows through Glenwood Canyon, and then through an arid valley made up of desert from Rifle to Parachute, through the desert canyon of De Beque Canyon, and into the arid desert of Grand Valley, where the city of Grand Junction is located.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Also prominent is the Grand Mesa, which lies to the southeast of Grand Junction; the high San Juan Mountains, a rugged mountain range; and to the north and west of the San Juan Mountains, the Colorado Plateau.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction, Colorado, at the confluence of the Colorado and Gunnison Rivers, is the largest city on the Western Slope.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction and Durango are the only major centers of television broadcasting west of the Continental Divide in Colorado, though most mountain resort communities publish daily newspapers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is located at the juncture of Interstate 70 and US 50, the only major highways in western Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is also along the major railroad of the Western Slope, the Union Pacific.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] This railroad also provides the tracks for Amtrak's *California Zephyr* passenger train, which crosses the Rocky Mountains between Denver and Grand Junction.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes multiple notable destinations in the Colorado Rocky Mountains, including Glenwood Springs, with its resort hot springs, and the ski resorts of Aspen, Breckenridge, Vail, Crested Butte, Steamboat Springs, and Telluride.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Higher education in western and southwestern Colorado includes Colorado Mesa University in Grand Junction, Western Colorado University in Gunnison, Fort Lewis College in Durango, and Colorado Mountain College campuses in Glenwood Springs and Steamboat Springs.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument in the southwest corner of Colorado marks the common boundary of Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah, the only such place in the United States.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The climate of Colorado is more complex than states outside of the Mountain States region.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Unlike most other states, southern Colorado is not always warmer than northern Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Most of Colorado is made up of mountains, foothills, high plains, and desert lands.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Mountains and surrounding valleys greatly affect the local climate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Northeast, east, and southeast Colorado are mostly the high plains, while Northern Colorado is a mix of high plains, foothills, and mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Northwest and west Colorado are predominantly mountainous, with some desert lands mixed in.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Southwest and southern Colorado are a complex mixture of desert and mountain areas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The climate of the Eastern Plains is semi-arid (Köppen climate classification: *BSk*) with low humidity and moderate precipitation, usually from 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually, although many areas near the rivers are semi-humid climate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The area is known for its abundant sunshine and cool, clear nights, which give this area a great average diurnal temperature range.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The difference between the highs of the days and the lows of the nights can be considerable as warmth dissipates to space during clear nights, the heat radiation not being trapped by clouds.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Front Range urban corridor, where most of the population of Colorado resides, lies in a pronounced precipitation shadow as a result of being on the lee side of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In summer, this area can have many days above 95 °F (35 °C) and often 100 °F (38 °C).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On the plains, the winter lows usually range from 25 to −10 °F (−4 to −23 °C).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] About 75% of the precipitation falls within the growing season, from April to September, but this area is very prone to droughts.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Most of the precipitation comes from thunderstorms, which can be severe, and from major snowstorms that occur in the winter and early spring.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Otherwise, winters tend to be mostly dry and cold.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In much of the region, March is the snowiest month.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] April and May are normally the rainiest months, while April is the wettest month overall.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Front Range cities closer to the mountains tend to be warmer in the winter due to Chinook winds which warm the area, sometimes bringing temperatures of 70 °F (21 °C) or higher in the winter.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The average July temperature is 55 °F (13 °C) in the morning and 90 °F (32 °C) in the afternoon.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The average January temperature is 18 °F (−8 °C) in the morning and 48 °F (9 °C) in the afternoon, although variation between consecutive days can be 40 °F (4 °C).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Just west of the plains and into the foothills, there is a wide variety of climate types.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Locations merely a few miles apart can experience entirely different weather depending on the topography.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Most valleys have a semi-arid climate, not unlike the eastern plains, which transitions to an alpine climate at the highest elevations.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Microclimates also exist in local areas that run nearly the entire spectrum of climates, including subtropical highland (*Cfb/Cwb*), humid subtropical (*Cfa*), humid continental (*Dfa/Dfb*), Mediterranean (*Csa/Csb*) and subarctic (*Dfc*).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Extreme weather changes are common in Colorado, although a significant portion of the extreme weather occurs in the least populated areas of the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Thunderstorms are common east of the Continental Divide in the spring and summer, yet are usually brief.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Hail is a common sight in the mountains east of the Divide and across the eastern Plains, especially the northeast part of the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Hail is the most commonly reported warm-season severe weather hazard, and occasionally causes human injuries, as well as significant property damage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The eastern Plains are subject to some of the biggest hail storms in North America.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Notable examples are the severe hailstorms that hit Denver on July 11, 1990, and May 8, 2017, the latter being the costliest ever in the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Eastern Plains are part of the extreme western portion of Tornado Alley; some damaging tornadoes in the Eastern Plains include the 1990 Limon F3 tornado and the 2008 Windsor EF3 tornado, which devastated a small town.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Portions of the eastern Plains see especially frequent tornadoes, both those spawned from mesocyclones in supercell thunderstorms and from less intense landspouts, such as within the Denver convergence vorticity zone (DCVZ).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The Plains are also susceptible to occasional floods and particularly severe flash floods, which are caused both by thunderstorms and by the rapid melting of snow in the mountains during warm weather.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Notable examples include the 1965 Denver Flood, the Big Thompson River flooding of 1976 and the 2013 Colorado floods.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Hot weather is common during summers in Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The city's record in 1901 for the number of consecutive days above 90 °F (32 °C) was broken during the summer of 2008.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The new record of 24 consecutive days surpassed the previous record by almost a week.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Much of Colorado is very dry, with the state averaging only 17 inches (430 mm) of precipitation per year statewide.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The state rarely experiences a time when some portion is not in some degree of drought.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The lack of precipitation contributes to the severity of wildfires in the state, such as the Hayman Fire of 2002.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Other notable fires include the Fourmile Canyon Fire of 2010, the Waldo Canyon Fire and High Park Fire of June 2012, and the Black Forest Fire of June 2013.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Even these fires were exceeded in severity by the Pine Gulch Fire, Cameron Peak Fire, and East Troublesome Fire in 2020, all being the three largest fires in Colorado history (see 2020 Colorado wildfires).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] And the Marshall Fire which started on December 30, 2021, while not the largest in state history, was the most destructive ever in terms of property loss (see Marshall Fire).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] However, some of the mountainous regions of Colorado receive a huge amount of moisture from winter snowfalls.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The spring melts of these snows often cause great waterflows in the Yampa River, the Colorado River, the Rio Grande, the Arkansas River, the North Platte River, and the South Platte River.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Water flowing out of the Colorado Rocky Mountains is a very significant source of water for the farms, towns, and cities of the southwest states of New Mexico, Arizona, Utah, and Nevada, as well as the Midwest, such as Nebraska and Kansas, and the southern states of Oklahoma and Texas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] A significant amount of water is also diverted for use in California; occasionally (formerly naturally and consistently), the flow of water reaches northern Mexico.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Climate change in Colorado encompasses the effects of climate change, attributed to man-made increases in atmospheric greenhouse gases, in the U.S. state of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 2019 *The Denver Post* reported that "[i]ndividuals living in southeastern Colorado are more vulnerable to potential health effects from climate change than residents in other parts of the state".
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Most of the state has warmed one or two degrees (F) in the last century.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Throughout the western United States, heat waves are becoming more common, snow is melting earlier in spring, and less water flows through the Colorado River.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Rising temperatures and recent droughts in the region have killed many trees by drying out soils, increasing the risk of forest fires, or enabling outbreaks of forest insects.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In the coming decades, the changing climate is likely to decrease water availability and agricultural yields in Colorado, and further increase the risk of wildfires".
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The highest official ambient air temperature ever recorded in Colorado was 115 °F (46.1 °C) on July 20, 2019, at John Martin Dam.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The lowest official air temperature was −61 °F (−51.7 °C) on February 1, 1985, at Maybell.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Despite its mountainous terrain, Colorado experiences less seismic activity than states like California and Alaska.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] There are over 90 potentially active faults, and since 1867, Colorado has experienced 700 recorded earthquakes of magnitude 2.5 or higher.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] National Earthquake Information Center is located in Golden.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] On August 22, 2011, a 5.3 magnitude earthquake occurred 9 miles (14 km) west-southwest of the city of Trinidad.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] There were no casualties and only a small amount of damage was reported.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] It was the second-largest earthquake in Colorado's history, the largest being a magnitude 6.6 earthquake, recorded in 1882.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Four minor earthquakes rattled Colorado on August 24, 2018, ranging from magnitude 2.9 to 4.3.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] As of June 2020, there were 525 recorded earthquakes in Colorado since 1973, a majority of which range 2 to 3.5 on the Richter scale.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] A process of extirpation by trapping and poisoning of the gray wolf (*Canis lupus*) from Colorado in the 1930s saw the last wild wolf in the state shot in 1945.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] A wolf pack recolonized Moffat County, Colorado in northwestern Colorado in 2019.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Cattle farmers have expressed concern that a returning wolf population potentially threatens their herds.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Coloradans voted to reintroduce gray wolves in 2020, with the state committing to a plan to have a population in the state by 2022 and permitting non-lethal methods of driving off wolves attacking livestock and pets.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Despite being an artificially-introduced species, the state declared mountain goats a native species in 1993.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] In 2013, 2014, and 2019, an unknown illness killed nearly all mountain goat kids, leading to a Colorado Parks and Wildlife investigation.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The native population of pronghorn in Colorado has varied wildly over the last century, reaching a low of only 15,000 individuals during the 1960s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] However, conservation efforts succeeded in bringing the stable population back up to roughly 66,000 by 2013.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The population was estimated to have reached 85,000 by 2019 and had increasingly more run-ins with the increased suburban housing along the eastern Front Range.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] State wildlife officials suggested that landowners would need to modify fencing to allow the greater number of pronghorns to move unabated through the newly developed land.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Pronghorns are most readily found in the northern and eastern portions of the state, with some populations also in the western San Juan Mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] Common wildlife found in the mountains of Colorado include mule deer, southwestern red squirrel, golden-mantled ground squirrel, yellow-bellied marmot, moose, American pika, and red fox, all at exceptionally high numbers, though moose are not native to the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The foothills include deer, fox squirrel, desert cottontail, mountain cottontail, and coyote.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p01] The prairies are home to black-tailed prairie dog, the endangered swift fox, American badger, and white-tailed jackrabbit.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Like the federal government and all other U.S. states, Colorado's state constitution provides for three branches of government: the legislative, the executive, and the judicial branches.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Governor of Colorado heads the state's executive branch.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The current governor is Jared Polis, a Democrat.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's other statewide elected executive officers are the Lieutenant Governor of Colorado (elected on a ticket with the Governor), Secretary of State of Colorado, Colorado State Treasurer, and Attorney General of Colorado, all of whom serve four-year terms.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The seven-member Colorado Supreme Court is the state's highest court.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Colorado Court of Appeals, with 22 judges, sits in divisions of three judges each.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is divided into 23 judicial districts, each of which has a district court and a county court with limited jurisdiction.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state also has specialized water courts, which sit in seven distinct divisions around the state and which decide matters relating to water rights and the use and administration of water.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state legislative body is the Colorado General Assembly, which is made up of two houses – the House of Representatives and the Senate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The House has 65 members and the Senate has 35.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] As of April 2026, the Democratic Party holds a 23 to 12 majority in the Senate and a 43 to 22 majority in the House.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] State sales taxes and many state-collected local sales taxes are administered and collected by the Colorado Department of Revenue.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado was once considered a swing state, but has become a relatively safe blue state in both state and federal elections since the late 2010s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In presidential elections, it had not been won until 2020 by double digits since 1984 and has backed the winning candidate in 9 of the last 11 elections.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Coloradans have elected 17 Democrats and 12 Republicans to the governorship in the last 100 years.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In presidential politics, Colorado was considered a reliably Republican state during the post-World War II era, voting for the Democratic candidate only in 1948, 1964, and 1992.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] However, it became a competitive swing state in the 1990s.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Since the mid-2000s, it has swung heavily to the Democrats, voting for Barack Obama in 2008 and 2012, Hillary Clinton in 2016, Joe Biden in 2020, and Kamala Harris in 2024.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado politics exhibits a contrast between conservative cities such as Colorado Springs and Grand Junction, and liberal cities such as Boulder and Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Democrats are strongest in metropolitan Denver, the college towns of Fort Collins and Boulder, southern Colorado (including Pueblo), and several western ski resort counties.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Republicans are strongest in the Eastern Plains, Colorado Springs, Greeley, and far Western Colorado near Grand Junction.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In a 2020 study, Colorado was ranked as the seventh easiest state for citizens to vote in.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado was the first state in the union to enact, by voter referendum, a law extending suffrage to women.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] That initiative was approved by the state's voters on November 7, 1893.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On the November 8, 1932, ballot, Colorado approved the repeal of alcohol prohibition more than a year before the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution was ratified.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has banned, via C.R.S. section 12-6-302, the sale of motor vehicles on Sunday since at least 1953.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 1972, Colorado voters rejected a referendum proposal to fund the 1976 Winter Olympics, which had been scheduled to be held in the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver had been chosen by the International Olympic Committee as the host city on May 12, 1970.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Supreme Court found that preventing protected status based upon homosexuality or bisexuality did not satisfy the Equal Protection Clause.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2006, voters passed Amendment 43, which banned same-sex marriage in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] That initiative was nullified by the U.S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Supreme Court's 2015 decision in *Obergefell v.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2024, Colorado residents voted to establish an explicit right to abortion in Colorado's state constitution and to repeal Amendment 43's defunct marriage ban.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2012, voters amended the state constitution protecting the "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate cannabis like alcohol.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The first recreational marijuana shops in Colorado, and by extension the United States, opened their doors on January 1, 2014.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On October 30, 2019, Colorado became the first state to accept digital ID via its myColorado app.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state-issued digital identifications will be considered valid when Real ID enforcement begins in 2025, in line with the Real ID Act of 2005.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] By November 2022 The Colorado Governor's Office of Information Technology announced that the myColorado app had over 1 million users.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On December 19, 2023, the Colorado Supreme Court ruled that Donald Trump was disqualified from the 2024 United States presidential election in part due to his alleged incitement of the January 6 United States Capitol attack.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On March 4, 2024, the United States Supreme Court overruled the Colorado decision.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The State of Colorado is divided into 64 counties.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Two of these counties, the City and County of Broomfield and the City and County of Denver, have consolidated city and county governments.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Counties are important units of government in Colorado since there are no civil townships or other minor civil divisions.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous county in Colorado is El Paso County, the home of the City of Colorado Springs.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The second most populous county is the City and County of Denver, the state capital.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Five of the 64 counties now have more than 500,000 residents, while 12 have fewer than 5,000 residents.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The ten most populous Colorado counties are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Mesa County is the most populous county on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The least populous Colorado county is Hinsdale County with 747 residents.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has 273 active incorporated municipalities, comprising 198 towns, 73 cities, and two consolidated city and county governments.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] At the 2020 United States census, 4,299,942 of the 5,773,714 Colorado residents (74.47%) lived in one of these municipalities.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Another 714,417 residents (12.37%) lived in one of the 210 census-designated places, while the remaining 759,355 residents (13.15%) lived in the many rural and mountainous areas of the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado municipalities operate under one of five types of municipal governing authority.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado currently has two consolidated city and county governments, 61 home rule cities, 12 statutory cities, 35 home rule towns, 161 statutory towns, and one territorial charter municipality.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous municipality is the City and County of Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has 12 municipalities with more than 100,000 residents, and 17 with fewer than 100 residents.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The 16 most populous Colorado municipalities are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The City of Grand Junction is the most populous municipality on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Town of Carbonate has had no year-round population since the 1890 census due to its severe winter weather and difficult access.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In addition to its 272 municipalities, Colorado has 210 unincorporated census-designated places (CDPs) and many other small communities.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous unincorporated community in Colorado is Highlands Ranch south of Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The seven most populous CDPs are located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Clifton CDP is the most populous CDP on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has more than 4,000 special districts, most with property tax authority.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] These districts may provide health services, ambulance, schools, law enforcement, fire protection, water, sewage, drainage, irrigation, transportation, recreation, infrastructure, cultural facilities, business support, redevelopment, or other services.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Some of these districts have the authority to levy sales tax as well as property tax and use fees.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The 17 core-based statistical areas in the U.S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Most recently on July 21, 2023, the Office of Management and Budget defined 21 statistical areas for Colorado comprising four combined statistical areas, seven metropolitan statistical areas, and ten micropolitan statistical areas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous of the seven metropolitan statistical areas in Colorado is the 10-county Denver–Aurora–Centennial, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area with a population of 2,963,821 at the 2020 United States census, an increase of +15.29% since the 2010 census.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The more extensive 12-county Denver–Aurora–Greeley, CO Combined Statistical Area had a population of 3,623,560 at the 2020 census, an increase of +17.23% since the 2010 census.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous extended metropolitan region in Rocky Mountain Region is the 18-county Front Range Urban Corridor along the northeast face of the Southern Rocky Mountains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] This region with Denver at its center had a population of 5,055,344 at the 2020 census, an increase of +16.65% since the 2010 census.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The United States Census Bureau estimated the population of Colorado on July 1, 2024, at 5,957,493, a 3.2% increase since the 2020 United States census.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Coloradan Hispanics and Latinos (of any race and heritage) made up 20.7% of the population.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] According to the 2000 census, the largest ancestry groups in Colorado are German (22%), Mexican (18%), Irish (12%), and English (12%).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Persons reporting German ancestry are especially numerous in the Front Range, the Rockies (west-central counties), and Eastern parts/High Plains.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has a high proportion of Hispanic, mostly Mexican-American, citizens in Metropolitan Denver, Colorado Springs, as well as the smaller cities of Greeley and Pueblo, and elsewhere.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Southern, Southwestern, and Southeastern Colorado have a large number of Hispanos, the descendants of the early settlers of colonial Spanish origin.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Census Bureau reported Colorado's population as 8.2% Hispanic and 90.3% non-Hispanic White.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Hispanic population of Colorado has continued to grow quickly over the past decades.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] By 2019, Hispanics made up 22% of Colorado's population, and Non-Hispanic Whites made up 70%.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Spoken English in Colorado has many Spanish idioms.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado also has some large African-American communities located in Denver, in the neighborhoods of Montbello, Five Points, Whittier, and many other East Denver areas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In the 2020 Census, 234,828 Colorado residents were identified as African American (of the total 5,773,714).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Arapahoe, at 10.8% African American, was the only one of the state's 64 counties where African Americans make up more than 10% of the population.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] African Americans in the seven counties of Arapahoe (70,787), Denver (64,038), El Paso (43,822), Adams (17,463), Jefferson (7,356), Douglas (5,160), and Weld (4,539) make up more than 90% of all African Americans in the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The population of Native Americans in the state is small.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Native Americans are concentrated in metropolitan Denver and the southwestern corner of Colorado, where there are two Ute reservations.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The majority of Colorado's immigrants are from Mexico, India, China, Vietnam, Korea, Germany and Canada.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] There were a total of 70,331 births in Colorado in 2006.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] (Birth rate of 14.6 per thousand.) In 2007, non-Hispanic Whites were involved in 59.1% of all births.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Some 14.06% of those births involved a non-Hispanic White person and someone of a different race, most often with a couple including one Hispanic.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] A birth where at least one Hispanic person was involved counted for 43% of the births in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Per the 2000 census, the Hispanic population is estimated to be 918,899, or approximately 20% of the state's total population.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has the 5th-largest population of Mexican-Americans, behind California, Texas, Arizona, and Illinois.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In percentages, Colorado has the 6th-highest percentage of Mexican-Americans, behind New Mexico, California, Texas, Arizona, and Nevada.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2011, 46% of Colorado's population younger than the age of one were minorities, meaning that they had at least one parent who was not non-Hispanic White.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2017, Colorado recorded the second-lowest fertility rate in the United States outside of New England, after Oregon, at 1.63 children per woman.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Significant contributing factors to the decline in pregnancies were the Title X Family Planning Program and an intrauterine device grant from Warren Buffett's family.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] English, the official language of the state, is the most commonly spoken language in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The second most commonly spoken language in the state is Spanish.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Colorado River Numic language, also known as the Ute dialect, is still spoken in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Major religious affiliations of the people of Colorado as of 2014 were 64% Christian, of whom there are 44% Protestant, 16% Roman Catholic, 3% Mormon, and 1% Eastern Orthodox.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Other religious breakdowns according to the Pew Research Center were 1% Judaism, 1% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, and 4% other.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Secular Coloradans made up 29% of the population.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2020, according to the Public Religion Research Institute, Christianity was 66% of the population.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Judaism was also reported to have increased in this separate study, forming 2% of the religious landscape, while the religiously unaffiliated were reported to form 28% of the population in this separate study.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2022, the same organization reported 61% was Christian (39% Protestant, 19% Catholic, 2% Mormon, 1% Eastern Orthodox), 2% New Age, 1% Jewish, 1% Hindu, and 34% religiously unaffiliated.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] According to the Association of Religion Data Archives, the largest Christian denominations by the number of adherents in 2010 were the Catholic Church with 811,630; multi-denominational Evangelical Protestants with 229,981; and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 151,433.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2020, the Association of Religion Data Archives determined the largest Christian denominations were Catholics (873,236), non/multi/inter-denominational Protestants (406,798), and Mormons (150,509).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Throughout its non-Christian population, there were 12,500 Hindus, 7,101 Hindu Yogis, and 17,369 Buddhists at the 2020 study.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Our Lady of Guadalupe Catholic Church was the first permanent Catholic parish in modern-day Colorado and was constructed by Spanish colonists from New Mexico in modern-day Conejos.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Latin Church Catholics are served by three dioceses: the Archdiocese of Denver and the Dioceses of Colorado Springs and Pueblo.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The first permanent settlement by members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Colorado arrived from Mississippi and initially camped along the Arkansas River just east of the present-day site of Pueblo.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is generally considered among the healthiest states by behavioral and healthcare researchers.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Among the positive contributing factors is the state's well-known outdoor recreation opportunities and initiatives.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] However, there is a stratification of health metrics with wealthier counties such as Douglas and Pitkin performing significantly better relative to southern, less wealthy counties such as Huerfano and Las Animas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] According to several studies, Coloradans have the lowest rates of obesity of any state in the US.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] As of 2018, 24% of the population was considered medically obese, and while the lowest in the nation, the percentage had increased from 17% in 2004.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] According to a report in the *Journal of the American Medical Association*, residents of Colorado had a 2014 life expectancy of 80.21 years, the longest of any U.S. state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 10,397 homeless people in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The number of employer establishments is 174,258.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's gross domestic product in 2025 was $584.3 billion.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's per capita personal income was $86,181 in 2025, ranking Colorado 10th in the nation.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Median Annual Household Income in 2016 was $70,666, 8th in the nation.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's economy broadened from its mid-19th-century roots in mining when irrigated agriculture developed, and by the late 19th century, raising livestock had become important.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Early industry was based on the extraction and processing of minerals and agricultural products.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Current agricultural products are cattle, wheat, dairy products, corn, and hay.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2025, small businesses made up 99.5% of Colorado businesses, and employed 48.6% of the state's work force.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Geological Survey and other government agencies at the Denver Federal Center near Lakewood; the Denver Mint, Buckley Space Force Base, the Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals, and the Byron G.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Rogers Federal Building and United States Courthouse in Denver; and a federal Supermax Prison and other federal prisons near Cañon City.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In addition to these and other federal agencies, Colorado has abundant National Forest land and four National Parks that contribute to federal ownership of 24,615,788 acres (99,617 km2) of land in Colorado, or 37% of the total area of the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In the second half of the 20th century, the industrial and service sectors expanded greatly.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's economy is diversified and is notable for its concentration on scientific research and high-technology industries.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Other industries include food processing, transportation equipment, machinery, chemical products, the extraction of metals such as gold (see Gold mining in Colorado), silver, and molybdenum.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado now also has the largest annual production of beer in any state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver is an important financial center.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's diverse geography and majestic mountains attract millions of tourists every year, including 85.2 million in 2018.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Tourism contributes greatly to Colorado's economy, with tourists generating $22.3 billion in 2018.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Several nationally known brand names have originated in Colorado factories and laboratories.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] From Denver came the forerunner of telecommunications giant Qwest in 1879, Samsonite luggage in 1910, Gates belts and hoses in 1911, and Russell Stover Candies in 1923.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Kuner canned vegetables began in Brighton in 1864.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] From Golden came Coors beer in 1873, CoorsTek industrial ceramics in 1920, and Jolly Rancher candy in 1949.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] CF&I railroad rails, wire, nails, and pipe debuted in Pueblo in 1892.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Holly Sugar was first milled from beets in Holly in 1905, and later moved its headquarters to Colorado Springs.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The present-day Swift packed meat of Greeley evolved from Monfort of Colorado, Inc., established in 1930.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Estes model rockets were launched in Penrose in 1958.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Fort Collins has been the home of Woodward Governor Company's motor controllers (governors) since 1870, and Waterpik dental water jets and showerheads since 1962.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Celestial Seasonings herbal teas have been made in Boulder since 1969.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Rocky Mountain Chocolate Factory made its first candy in Durango in 1981.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has a flat 4.63% income tax, regardless of income level.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On November 3, 2020, voters authorized an initiative to lower that income tax rate to 4.55 percent.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Unlike most states, which calculate taxes based on federal *adjusted gross income*, Colorado taxes are based on *taxable income*—income after federal exemptions and federal itemized (or standard) deductions.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's state sales tax is 2.9% on retail sales.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] When state revenues exceed state constitutional limits, according to Colorado's Taxpayer Bill of Rights legislation, full-year Colorado residents can claim a sales tax refund on their individual state income tax return.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Many counties and cities charge their own rates, in addition to the base state rate.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] There are also certain county and special district taxes that may apply.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Real estate and personal business property are taxable in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's senior property tax exemption was temporarily suspended by the Colorado Legislature in 2003.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The tax break was scheduled to return for the assessment year 2006, payable in 2007.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] As of May 2025, the state's unemployment rate was 4.8%.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The West Virginia teachers' strike in 2018 inspired teachers in other states, including Colorado, to take similar action.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Corn is grown in the Eastern Plains of Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Arid conditions and drought negatively impacted yields in 2020 and 2022.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has significant hydrocarbon resources.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] According to the Energy Information Administration, Colorado hosts seven of the largest natural gas fields in the United States, and two of the largest oil fields.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Conventional and unconventional natural gas output from several Colorado basins typically accounts for more than five percent of annual U.S. natural gas production.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's oil shale deposits hold an estimated 1 trillion barrels (160 km3) of oil—nearly as much oil as the entire world's proven oil reserves.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Substantial deposits of bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite coal are found in the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Uranium mining in Colorado goes back to 1872, when pitchblende ore was taken from gold mines near Central City, Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Not counting byproduct uranium from phosphate, Colorado is considered to have the third-largest uranium reserves of any U.S. state, behind Wyoming and New Mexico.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] When Colorado and Utah dominated radium mining from 1910 to 1922, uranium and vanadium were the byproducts (giving towns like present-day Superfund site Uravan their names).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Uranium price increases from 2001 to 2007 prompted several companies to revive uranium mining in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] During the 1940s certain communities–including Naturita and Paradox–earned the moniker of "yellowcake towns" from their relationship with uranium mining.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Price drops and financing problems in late 2008 forced these companies to cancel or scale back the uranium-mining project.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] As of 2016, there were no major uranium mining operations in the state, though plans existed to restart production.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's high Rocky Mountain ridges and eastern plains offer wind power potential, and geologic activity in the mountain areas provides the potential for geothermal power development.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Much of the state is sunny and could produce solar power.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Major rivers flowing from the Rocky Mountains offer hydroelectric power resources.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Several film productions have been shot on location in Colorado, especially prominent Westerns like *True Grit*, *The Searchers*, *City Slickers,* *Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid, and My Life With the Walter Boys*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Several historic military forts, railways with trains still operating, and mining ghost towns have been used and transformed for historical accuracy in well-known films.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] There are also several scenic highways and mountain passes that helped to feature the open road in films such as *Vanishing Point*, *Bingo* and *Starman*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Some Colorado landmarks have been featured in films, such as The Stanley Hotel in *Dumb and Dumber* and *The Shining* and the Sculptured House in *Sleeper*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2015, *Furious 7* was to film driving sequences on Pikes Peak Highway in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The TV adult-animated series *South Park* takes place in central Colorado in the titular town.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Additionally, the TV series *Good Luck Charlie* was set, but not filmed, in Denver, Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Colorado Office of Film and Television has noted that more than 400 films have been shot in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On March 27, 2025, it was announced Sundance Film Festival would move to Boulder starting in 2027 after reaching a deal for a ten-year duration.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Many notable writers have lived or spent extended periods in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] *5280*, a Denver magazine, wrote in 2015 that Kent Haruf is "widely considered [to be] Colorado's finest novelist"; Haruf set his novels in the fictional high plains Colorado town of Holt.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Beat Generation writers Jack Kerouac and Neal Cassady lived in and around Denver for several years each.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Irish playwright Oscar Wilde visited Colorado on his tour of the United States in 1882, writing in his 1906 *Impressions of America* that Leadville was "the richest city in the world.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is known for its Southwest and Rocky Mountain cuisine, with Mexican restaurants found throughout the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Boulder was named America's Foodiest Town 2010 by Bon Appétit.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Boulder, and Colorado in general, is home to several national food and beverage companies, top-tier restaurants and farmers' markets.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Boulder also has more Master Sommeliers per capita than any other city, including San Francisco and New York.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver is known for steak, but now has a diverse culinary scene with many restaurants.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Polidori Sausage is a brand of pork products available in supermarkets, which originated in Colorado, in the early 20th century.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Food & Wine Classic is held annually each June in Aspen.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Aspen also has a reputation as the culinary capital of the Rocky Mountain region.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado wines include varietals that have attracted favorable notice from outside the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] With wines made from traditional *Vitis vinifera* grapes along with wines made from cherries, peaches, plums, and honey, Colorado wines have won top national and international awards for their quality.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's grape growing regions contain the highest elevation vineyards in the United States, with most viticulture in the state practiced between 4,000 and 7,000 feet (1,219 and 2,134 m) above sea level.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The mountain climate ensures warm summer days and cool nights.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to two designated American Viticultural Areas of the Grand Valley AVA and the West Elks AVA, where most of the vineyards in the state are located.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] However, an increasing number of wineries are located along the Front Range.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2018, Wine Enthusiast Magazine named Colorado's Grand Valley AVA in Mesa County, Colorado, as one of the Top Ten wine travel destinations in the world.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to many nationally praised microbreweries, including New Belgium Brewing Company, Odell Brewing Company, and Great Divide Brewing Company.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The area of northern Colorado near and between the cities of Denver, Boulder, and Fort Collins is known as the "Napa Valley of Beer" due to its high density of craft breweries.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is open to cannabis (marijuana) tourism.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] With the adoption of the 64th state amendment in 2012, Colorado became the first state in the union to legalize marijuana for medicinal (2000), industrial (referring to hemp, 2012), and recreational (2012) use.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's marijuana industry sold $1.31 billion worth of marijuana in 2016 and $1.26 billion in the first three-quarters of 2017.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state generated tax, fee, and license revenue of $194 million in 2016 on legal marijuana sales.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado regulates hemp as any part of the plant with less than 0.3% THC.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On April 4, 2014, Senate Bill 14–184 addressing oversight of Colorado's industrial hemp program was first introduced, ultimately being signed into law by Governor John Hickenlooper on May 31, 2014.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On November 7, 2000, 54% of Colorado voters passed Amendment 20, which amends the Colorado State constitution to allow the medical use of marijuana.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Currently, Colorado has listed "eight medical conditions for which patients can use marijuana—cancer, glaucoma, HIV/AIDS, muscle spasms, seizures, severe pain, severe nausea and cachexia, or dramatic weight loss and muscle atrophy".
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] While governor, John Hickenlooper allocated about half of the state's $13 million "Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund" to medical research in the 2014 budget.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] By 2018, the Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund was the "largest pool of pot money in the state" and was used to fund programs including research into pediatric applications for controlling autism symptoms.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On November 6, 2012, voters amended the state constitution to protect "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate marijuana in a manner similar to alcohol.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's primary mode of transportation (in terms of passengers) is its highway system.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Interstate 25 (I-25) is the primary north–south highway in the state, connecting Pueblo, Colorado Springs, Denver, and Fort Collins, and extending north to Wyoming and south to New Mexico.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] It connects Grand Junction and the mountain communities with Denver and enters Utah and Kansas.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The state is home to a network of US and Colorado highways that provide access to all principal areas of the state.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Many smaller communities are connected to this network only via county roads.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver International Airport (DIA) is the third-busiest domestic U.S. and international airport in the world by passenger traffic.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] DIA handles by far the largest volume of commercial air traffic in Colorado and is the busiest U.S. hub airport between Chicago and the Pacific coast, making Denver the most important airport for connecting passenger traffic in the western United States.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Public transportation bus services are offered both intra-city and inter-city—including the Denver metro area's RTD services.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Regional Transportation District (RTD) operates the popular RTD Bus & Rail transit system in the Denver Metropolitan Area.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] As of January 2013 the RTD rail system had 170 light-rail vehicles, serving 47 miles (76 km) of track.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In addition to local public transit, intercity bus service is provided by Burlington Trailways, Bustang and Greyhound Lines.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Amtrak operates two passenger rail lines in Colorado, the *California Zephyr* and *Southwest Chief*.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's contribution to world railroad history was forged principally by the Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad which began in 1870 and wrote the book on mountain railroading.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 1988 the "Rio Grande" was acquired, but was merged into, the Southern Pacific Railroad by their joint owner Philip Anschutz.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On September 11, 1996, Anschutz sold the combined company to the Union Pacific Railroad, creating the largest railroad network in the United States.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The Anschutz sale was partly in response to the earlier merger of Burlington Northern and Santa Fe which formed the large Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway (BNSF), Union Pacific's principal competitor in western U.S. railroading.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Both Union Pacific and BNSF have extensive freight operations in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's freight railroad network consists of 2,688 miles of Class I trackage.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] It is integral to the U.S. economy, being a critical artery for the movement of energy, agriculture, mining, and industrial commodities as well as general freight and manufactured products between the East and Midwest and the Pacific coast states.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In August 2014, Colorado began to issue driver licenses to aliens not lawfully in the United States who lived in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In September 2014, KCNC reported that 524 non-citizens were issued Colorado driver licenses that are normally issued to U.S. citizens living in Colorado.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The first institution of higher education in the Colorado Territory was the Colorado Seminary, opened on November 16, 1864, by the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The seminary closed in 1867 but reopened in 1880 as the University of Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] In 1870, the Bishop George Maxwell Randall of the Episcopal Church's Missionary District of Colorado and Parts Adjacent opened the first of what become the Colorado University Schools which would include the Territorial School of Mines opened in 1873 and sold to the Colorado Territory in 1874.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] These schools were initially run by the Episcopal Church.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] An 1861 territorial act called for the creation of a public university in Boulder, though it would not be until 1876 that the University of Colorado was founded.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The 1876 act also renamed Territorial School of Mines as the Colorado School of Mines.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] An 1870 territorial act created the Agricultural College of Colorado which opened in 1879.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The college was renamed the Colorado State College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts in 1935, and became Colorado State University in 1957.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The first Catholic college in Colorado was the Jesuit Sacred Heart College, which was founded in New Mexico in 1877, moved to Morrison in 1884, and to Denver in 1887.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The college was renamed Regis College in 1921 and Regis University in 1991.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1924, armed students patrolled the campus after a burning cross was found, the climax of tensions between Regis College and the locally-powerful Ku Klux Klan.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Following a 1950 assessment by the Service Academy Board, it was determined that there was a need to supplement the U.S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Military and Naval Academies with a third school that would provide commissioned officers for the newly independent Air Force.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1954, President Dwight Eisenhower signed a law that moved for the creation of a U.S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] Later that year, Colorado Springs was selected to host the new institution.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] From its establishment in 1955, until the construction of appropriate facilities in Colorado Springs was completed and opened in 1958, the Air Force Academy operated out of Lowry Air Force Base in Denver.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] With the opening of the Colorado Springs facility, the cadets moved to the new campus, though not in the full-kit march that some urban and campus legends suggest.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The first class of Space Force officers from the Air Force Academy commissioned on April 18, 2020.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The two Native American reservations remaining in Colorado are the Southern Ute Indian Reservation (1873; Ute dialect: *Kapuuta-wa Moghwachi Núuchi-u*) and Ute Mountain Ute Indian Reservation (1940; Ute dialect: *Wʉgama Núuchi*).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p02] The two abolished Indian reservations in Colorado were the Cheyenne and Arapaho Indian Reservation (1851–1870) and Ute Indian Reservation (1855–1873).
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p03] Colorado has five major professional sports leagues, all based in the Denver metropolitan area.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p03] Colorado is the least populous state with a franchise in each of the major professional sports leagues.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p03] The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb is a major hill climbing motor race held on the Pikes Peak Highway.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p03] The Cherry Hills Country Club has hosted several professional golf tournaments, including the U.S.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p03] Women's Open, PGA Championship and BMW Championship.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/colorado-p03] The following universities and colleges participate in the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division I.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Davis Hanson Waite was born on April 9, 1825, in Jamestown, New York, to Joseph Waite and Olive Davis Waite.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] He studied law and graduated from Jamestown Academy.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] In 1851, he married Frances Eliza Russell and together they had three children, Arthur, Olive and May Josephine.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Waite served in the state legislatures of Wisconsin in 1857, and Kansas in 1879.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Waite moved with his family to Leadville, Colorado, in 1879 to practice law.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] After his wife Frances died in November 1880, he moved to Aspen.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] In Aspen he started the local newspaper and served as secretary of the local assembly of the Knights of Labor.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Waite was elected to the Wisconsin Legislature as a Republican and ran a Republican newspaper in New York.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] In Colorado he edited the *Union Era*, a reform paper, and helped to organized the People's Party (Populists) national convention.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] In 1892 he was nominated as the Populist candidate for Governor of Colorado and he was inaugurated on January 10, 1893.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] His election coincided with the Panic of 1893 which hit the silver mining industry in Colorado particularly hard.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] In 1894, the Western Federation of Miners went on a five-month strike and Waite intervened on behalf of the union, ordering the deployment of the state militia to support and protect the miners.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] That same year Waite supported the American Railroad Union during the national Pullman Strike.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] As governor he was also instrumental in the passage of women's suffrage in Colorado, the second state to do so.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] In 1893, a new municipal charter was given to Denver by the state legislature that decentralized much of the mayor's powers into six different administrative departments, two of which were elected, two appointed by the mayor, and the remaining two appointed by the governor.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] The municipal board members appointed by the governor had complete financial control over the police, fire, and excise departments.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Governor Waite tried to overturn the corruption in Denver in 1894 by removing police and fire commissioners that he thought were shielding gamblers and prostitutes.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] The officials refused to leave their positions and were quickly joined by others who felt their jobs were threatened.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] They barricaded themselves in City Hall, and the state militia were sent to remove them.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Federal troops were called in from nearby Fort Logan to intervene and quell the civil strife.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Eventually Governor Waite agreed to withdraw the militia and allow the state Supreme Court to decide the case.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] The court ruled that the governor had authority to replace the commissioners, but he was reprimanded for bringing in the militia, in what became known as the "City Hall War".
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] He was defeated for reelection in 1894, but continued to be active in the Populist movement until his death in 1901.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] Waite died on November 27, 1901, while preparing Thanksgiving dinner at his home in Aspen.
[src:1893-colorado-women-s-suffrage-referendum/davis-hanson-waite] His house on West Francis Street in Aspen has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
